Did the patient notice? I felt as if I were disintegrating. I reached for a prescription pad, trying to steady my shaking hand.

snippet: Gelareh Asayesh on her confused feelings about covering herself according to Islamic precepts whenever she returns to Iran, where she grew up, from her home in US; drawing (M)
lead_paragraph: I grew up wearing the miniskirt to school, the veil to the mosque. In the Tehran of my childhood, women in bright sundresses shared the sidewalk with women swathed in black. The tension between the two ways of life was palpable. As a schoolgirl, I often cringed when my bare legs got leering or contemptuous glances. Yet, at times, I long for the days when I could walk the streets of my country with the wind in my hair. When clothes were clothes. In today's Iran, whatever I wear sends a message. If it's a chador, it embarrasses my Westernized relatives. If it's a skimpy scarf, I risk being accused of stepping on the blood of the martyrs who died in the war with Iraq. Each time I return to Tehran, I wait until the last possible moment, when my plane lands on the tarmac, to don the scarf and long jacket that many Iranian women wear in lieu of a veil. To wear hijab -- Islamic covering -- is to invite contradiction. Sometimes I hate it. Sometimes I value it.

lead_paragraph: ''They were the strong guys, who could do whatever they wanted,'' my husband said. ''Like the G.I.'s, like Gary Cooper. They were rich. All of them were kings: newspaper kings, zipper kings. They ate ketchup and mustard, and they wore Stetson hats and ridiculous ties.'' He is Italian and grew up in Rome in the 1950's and was reminiscing about what he thought of Americans as a child, his words conveying a mixture of awe and mild hostility.
